The family
Podoceridae Leach, 1814
is one of five families of the superfamily
Caprelloidea Leach, 1814
(
). Among which, Podoceridae closely resembles
Dulichiidae Dana, 1849
but differs in having a rectangular head and pereopod 7 attached ventrally (not posteroventrally) to pereonite 7 (cf.
). The family currently contains eight genera and 89 species (
). From Japanese waters, four podocerid species have been reported, and all of them were collected from localities shallower than 100 m depth (
;
).

Leipsuropus Stebbing, 1899
is one of eight podocerid genera characterized by i) pereonite 1 shorter than head, ii) segmented urosomites 1–3, and iii) two paired uropods(uropod2 absent).As with other podocerids, members of this genus are efficient climbers on algae and invertebrates such as sponges, holothuroids, asteroids, and ascidians (
;
;
). So far, four species have been reported:
Leipsuropus astericolus Ariyama, 2012
from 98 m depth in the Sea of Japan ;
Leipsuropus hongi Ariyama, 2012
from 108 m depth in the East China Sea;
Leipsuropus parasiticus ( Haswell, 1879 )
from ca. 5.5 m to 24 m depth along the southeastern coast of Australia ; and
Leipsuropus sinensis Ren, 2012
from 21–87 m depth in the Yellow Sea (Liaodong Bay) and the East China Sea (
).

